WINE QUALITY PREDICTION¶

This notebook serves as the documentation for the development of machine learning models for predicting the quality of wine based of its various properties such as alcohol,chlorides etc.The workflow includes verious steps such as data loading,preprocessing,feature engineering and training various models to evaluate their performance.

DATA LOADING¶

The red and white wine datasets are loaded and merged into single dataset with additional column to distinguish between wines.

In [2]:

#initializing criteria for data classification
def quality_classification(quality):
     if quality > 7 :
        return 'Good' 
     else :
         return 'Bad'

DATA BALANCING¶

Data balancing is the process of managing the classes so that the distribution is more even. It is crucial as one class may be overrepresented than the other class causing imbalance and poor performance of the model

In [22]:
#Using SMOTE for oversampling the underrepresented class
smote = SMOTE(sampling_strategy='auto', random_state=42)
x_resampled, y_resampled = smote.fit_resample(x, y)

x_train,x_test,y_train,y_test = train_test_split(x_resampled,y_resampled,test_size=0.2,random_state=42)

FEATURE SCALING¶

Feature scaling is the process of normalizing/standardizing the range of features in the dataset meaning that features can be represented in different scales such as if one feature is represented in dollars and another in liter the model may prioritize one feature over another.

In [27]:
#Standarizing the data so that the features are on same scale
scaler=StandardScaler()
scaled_x_train = scaler.fit_transform(x_train) #measuring the scale and tranforming training data  
scaled_x_test= scaler.transform(x_test) # transforming the test set into same scale as training set

MODEL IMPLEMENTATION¶

After splitting, the data are fitted into chosen algorithms such as Support Vector Machine (SVM), Decision Tree Classifier and Bagging Classifier. The model trains according to training data and learn hidden patterns and relationships between the independent and (target) dependent feature

In [28]:
#Training SVM model without hyperparameter tuning
#initializing the SVM model.
svm_model = SVC(random_state=42)
svm_model.fit(scaled_x_train, y_train)
svm_pred = svm_model.predict(scaled_x_test)
svm_accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, svm_pred)
print(f"SVM Accuracy: {svm_accuracy:.2f}")

#checking if the model is overfitting
#condition: if training accuracy - testing accuracy >5 =Overfitting
y_train_pred = svm_model.predict(x_train)
train_accuracy = accuracy_score(y_train, y_train_pred)
print(f"Training Accuracy: {train_accuracy:.4f}")
print(f"Testing Accuracy: {svm_accuracy:.4f}")

SVM Accuracy: 0.87
Training Accuracy: 0.4962
Testing Accuracy: 0.8690
In [29]:
#Training SVM model with hyperparameter tuning using GridSearch
#initializing the hyperparameter
svm_grid_param = {
    'C': [0.1, 1, 10, 50],
    'kernel': ['linear', 'rbf', 'poly'],
    'gamma': ['scale', 'auto'],
    }
svm_grid = GridSearchCV(SVC(random_state=42), param_grid=svm_grid_param, scoring='accuracy', cv=5)
svm_grid.fit(scaled_x_train, y_train)
grid_svm_model = svm_grid.best_estimator_
grid_svm_pred = grid_svm_model.predict(scaled_x_test)
grid_svm_accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test,grid_svm_pred)
print(f"Best SVM Parameters: {svm_grid.best_params_}")
grid_svm_accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, grid_svm_pred)
print(f"Grid SVM Accuracy: {grid_svm_accuracy:.2f}")
#checking if the model is overfitting
#condition: if training accuracy - testing accuracy >5 =Overfitting
y_train_pred = grid_svm_model.predict(scaled_x_train)
train_accuracy = accuracy_score(y_train, y_train_pred)
print(f"Training Accuracy: {train_accuracy:.4f}")
print(f"Testing Accuracy: {grid_svm_accuracy:.4f}")

Best SVM Parameters: {'C': 50, 'gamma': 'scale', 'kernel': 'rbf'}
Grid SVM Accuracy: 0.93
Training Accuracy: 0.9352
Testing Accuracy: 0.9321

In [34]:
# Create a figure for plotting the ROC curve
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 8))

# ROC and AUC for SVM before hyperparameter tuning
fpr_svm, tpr_svm, _ = roc_curve(y_test, svm_pred)
roc_auc_svm = auc(fpr_svm, tpr_svm)
plt.plot(fpr_svm, tpr_svm, color='blue', lw=2, label=f'SVM (AUC = {roc_auc_svm:.2f})')

# ROC and AUC for SVM after hyperparameter tuning
fpr_grid_svm, tpr_grid_svm,_= roc_curve(y_test, grid_svm_pred)
roc_auc_grid_svm = auc(fpr_grid_svm, tpr_grid_svm)
plt.plot(fpr_grid_svm, tpr_grid_svm, color='green', lw=2, label=f'Grid SVM (AUC = {roc_auc_grid_svm:.2f})')

# ROC and AUC for Decision Tree
fpr_tree, tpr_tree, _ = roc_curve(y_test, tree_pred)
roc_auc_tree = auc(fpr_tree, tpr_tree)
plt.plot(fpr_tree, tpr_tree, color='red', lw=2, label=f'Decision Tree (AUC = {roc_auc_tree:.2f})')

# ROC and AUC for Bagging Classifier
fpr_bagging, tpr_bagging, _ = roc_curve(y_test, bagging_pred)
roc_auc_bagging = auc(fpr_bagging, tpr_bagging)
plt.plot(fpr_bagging, tpr_bagging, color='orange', lw=2, label=f'Bagging Classifier (AUC = {roc_auc_bagging:.2f})')

# Adding the  line representing a worse model performance
plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], color='grey', lw=2, linestyle='--',label='Worst case')

# Adding plot labels and title

plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate')
plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate')
plt.title('ROC Curve for  Models')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

The ROC Curve is a visual representation of model performance across all thresholds.It shows the relationship between true positive rate and false positive rate. The Area under the curve (AUC) represents the probability that the model, if given a randomly chosen positive and negative example, will rank the positive higher than the negative. It summarizes the ROC curve in single number
